'''Geet-Gawai''' ([[Bhojpuri]]:गीत गवाई) also called '''Geet Gawai''' is a pre-wedding ceremony of [[Bhojpuri language|Bhojpuri]] speaking people of Indian descent in [[Mauritius]]. In 2016, this ritual was added to the [[UNESCO]]'s [[Intangible Cultural Heritage List]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/bhojpuri-folk-songs-in-mauritius-geet-gawai-01178|title = Bhojpuri folk songs in Mauritius, Geet-Gawai | accessdate = 2017-01-11 }}</ref> This pre-wedding ceremony is a combination of certain traditional rituals, prayers to the gods and the goddesses, songs, music and dance. The ceremony may be done at the residence of bride or the groom, and is carried out by female family members and neighbours. This ceremony represents collective cultural memory. By breaking barriers of caste and class, it contributes to building of smooth and cohesive community identity. Presently, Geet-Gawai has come out of the confines of being a family function, and public performances also take place. Now-a-days, apart from women, men are also participating in these events.
